= Getting Started: Your First Agent

This book has taught you the principles. Now here's the practical bit: which tool do you actually open on Monday morning?

The landscape changes fast, but as of early 2026, here are the main options for a non-programmer who wants to start working with agents.

== The Three Paths

=== Path 1: Chat-Based Agents (Free to Low Cost)

*What:* A conversation interface where you type instructions and the agent responds with text, code, analysis, or files.

*Best for:* Writing, analysis, brainstorming, drafting reports, creating templates — the kind of work from the Monday report walkthrough.

*Options:*
- *Claude* (claude.ai) — Free tier available. Pro plan (\$20/month) gives more usage and access to stronger models. This is the agent behind this book.
- *ChatGPT* (chat.openai.com) — Free tier available. Plus plan (\$20/month). Widely used, strong general capabilities.
- *Gemini* (gemini.google.com) — Free tier available. Integrates well with Google Workspace.

*How to start:* Sign up. Type a task. See what happens. Start with something low-stakes — summarise a document, draft an email, analyse a small dataset. Build from there.

=== Path 2: Coding Agents (For Building Software)

*What:* Agents that can write, edit, and run code directly. They work inside your project, create files, and build working software from your instructions.

*Best for:* Building apps like the window quoting tool. Creating websites, automating workflows, building tools.

*Options:*
- *Claude Code* (command line tool) — Included with Claude Pro plan. Works in your terminal. This is what powers the kind of build process described in the book.
- *Cursor* (cursor.com) — A code editor with built-in AI. Free tier available. Pro plan (\$20/month). Feels like a normal editor but the agent can write and modify code alongside you.
- *GitHub Copilot* (github.com/copilot) — Built into VS Code. \$10/month. More focused on code completion than full agent workflows, but very effective for developers.

*How to start:* If you're following the window quoting walkthrough, Cursor is the most approachable. Download it, open a new project, and start describing what you want in the chat panel. It creates the files for you.

=== Path 3: No-Code Agent Platforms

*What:* Visual tools that let you connect agents to services, automate workflows, and build processes without writing code.

*Best for:* Automating business processes. Connecting tools together. The kind of workflows covered in the "Extending the Crew's Reach" chapter.

*Options:*
- *Zapier* (zapier.com) — Connects thousands of apps. Free tier for basic automations. Plans from \$20/month.
- *Make* (make.com) — Similar to Zapier, more visual. Free tier available.
- *n8n* (n8n.io) — Open-source, self-hostable. Free to run yourself, cloud plans available.

*How to start:* Pick a simple automation. "When I get an email from a specific client, summarise it and post it to our team Slack channel." Build it in Zapier or Make. See how it feels.

== What You'll Need

*For chat-based agents:* A web browser. That's it.

*For coding agents:* A computer with a terminal (Mac or Linux is easiest), Node.js installed, and Git. If those words make you nervous, ask the chat-based agent to walk you through the setup — "How do I install Node.js and Git on my Mac?" is a perfectly good first prompt.

*For no-code platforms:* A web browser and accounts for the services you want to connect.

== The First Week

Here's a realistic schedule for getting started:

*Day 1:* Sign up for Claude or ChatGPT. Ask it to summarise a long email or document. Ask it to draft a reply. Get comfortable with the conversation.

*Day 2:* Try the Monday report exercise from the book. Export some real data, provide an example of what you want, and see what the agent produces.

*Day 3:* Ask the agent to help with something you've been putting off — a presentation outline, a project plan, a comparison of three options for a decision you need to make.

*Day 4:* Try giving the agent raw materials instead of descriptions. Notice the difference in output quality.

*Day 5:* Set up one small automation. An email template. A recurring report. Something that saves you fifteen minutes a week.

By Friday, you'll have a working sense of what agents can do, where they struggle, and how to get the best out of them. Everything else is iteration.

== The Cost

Most people can get meaningful value from free tiers. The \$20/month paid tiers are worth it if you're using agents daily — the limits are higher, the models are smarter, and the experience is smoother.

For context: \$20/month is less than a single hour of a freelancer's time. If the agent saves you two hours a week, the math is obvious.

== One More Thing

Don't wait until you feel ready. You won't. The best way to learn is to open the tool, give it a real task, and see what happens. The first output won't be perfect. That's fine. You iterate. That's literally the point of this entire book.

You have the principles. Now go get your hands dirty.
